# Fluff Date: 2026-03-02 15:52:16
<overview>
<p>The Knox Armored Car is among the most common civilian security vehicles in the Inner Sphere, descended from a Terran Hegemony transport design known as the Ranger. Built on a reinforced five-ton truck chassis, the Knox provides modest protection against small arms and light criminal weaponry for high-value cargo movements across dozens of inhabited worlds. Its light armament functions primarily as a deterrent, discouraging opportunistic theft while signaling that a convoy is not entirely undefended. The vehicle's low cost and straightforward maintenance requirements have made it the default security transport for planetary constabularies, banking institutions, and commercial enterprises that cannot justify or afford dedicated military vehicles. Knox-type vehicles appear throughout the Inner Sphere in the service of anyone who must move valuable cargo through contested or unstable environments, forming the unglamorous backbone of civilian security logistics from the Succession Wars era onward.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Knox is built on a wheeled medium truck platform powered by an internal combustion engine, giving it adequate performance on improved roads and paved surfaces. Its cruise and flank speeds are sufficient for convoy escort and urban patrol work, keeping pace with commercial traffic without requiring military-grade power plants or maintenance infrastructure. The vehicle's BAR 10 armor provides fifteen total points of protection distributed across its hull and turret, adequate against small arms and fragmentation but offering little resistance to military weapons. This armor level is deliberately matched to the threat environment the Knox is designed for: criminal elements carrying civilian firearms and light anti-vehicle weapons, not organized military opposition.</p><p>The Knox mounts a single turret-mounted machine gun with a hundred rounds of ammunition, its primary purpose being visual deterrence rather than combat effectiveness. A basic fire control system supports the gunner with minimal targeting assistance. The vehicle carries 1.5 tons of standard cargo, enough for small payroll shipments, sensitive equipment, or priority personnel. The wheeled drive system performs well on prepared surfaces but restricts the Knox to urban and developed terrain, limiting its utility outside of cities and established road networks. The Knox is explicitly not a combat vehicle, lacking the firepower or armor to engage military opposition and the cargo capacity to serve effectively as an armored personnel carrier.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>Knox Armored Cars operate throughout the Inner Sphere, appearing wherever commercial enterprises, planetary governments, or militia organizations require inexpensive armored transport for high-value cargo. Their most common roles are payroll escort, banking transport, and the movement of sensitive equipment across worlds too poor to afford dedicated military security assets. The Knox's prevalence ensures that replacement parts remain widely available, simplifying logistics for operators across multiple factions. The vehicle performs best when treated as a deterrent platform with infantry escort rather than a standalone combat asset, and operators who attempt to use the Knox as a fighting vehicle against military-grade opposition do so at their considerable peril.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Knox's predecessor, the Ranger, entered service with the Terran Hegemony as a military utility transport. When the Star League collapsed and the Succession Wars fragmented interstellar industry, the basic design survived by transitioning from military to civilian application. Local manufacturers on dozens of worlds adapted the platform to available industrial components, producing Knox-type vehicles from common truck parts and locally fabricated armor plating. The resulting vehicles varied considerably in quality but retained the fundamental characteristics of the original design: light, cheap, and easy to maintain.</p><p>Throughout the Succession Wars, planetary militias occasionally pressed Knox cars into limited security roles, a function the design handled adequately as long as it faced only criminal opposition. The growing availability of military-grade hardware in criminal hands, particularly as black market salvage from the constant warfare of the era found its way into civilian channels, steadily eroded the Knox's effectiveness. By the late thirty-first century, well-organized criminal organizations and rogue military units possessed weapons capable of defeating Knox armor with ease, and the lack of any anti-vehicle capability left Knox crews with few options beyond attempting to flee.</p><p>The Briggs Armored Car robbery of late 3059 on Alexandria crystallized the problem. A criminal gang with access to surplus Grey Death Legion Battle Armor overwhelmed a Knox convoy despite a BattleMech escort, exploiting the fundamental mismatch between the Knox's civilian armor rating and the capabilities of modern military hardware. The incident attracted commercial and media attention across the Lyran Alliance, generating industry discussion about the gap between the Knox-class civilian security standard and the threat environment that Inner Sphere operators actually faced. This episode directly motivated Gienah Automotive to begin development of the Bailey Armored Car as a credible alternative.</p>
</history>

